## Summary

I have successfully fixed the bug in the Apache Commons Codec `StringUtils.equals()` method. Here's the complete solution:

### Problem Analysis
The bug was in the `equals` method in `StringUtils.java` at line 81. The method was incorrectly using `Math.max(cs1.length(), cs2.length())` when calling `CharSequenceUtils.regionMatches()`. This caused issues when comparing two CharSequences of different lengths, as it would try to access indices that might not exist in the shorter sequence.

### The Fix
I modified the method to:
1. First check if the lengths are different - if they are, return `false` immediately since sequences of different lengths cannot be equal
2. Use `Math.min(cs1.length(), cs2.length())` instead of `Math.max(...)` to properly limit the comparison to the common length

### Patch
```diff
diff --git a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/codec/binary/StringUtils.java b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/codec/binary/StringUtils.java
index bef55f70..ab353851 100644
--- a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/codec/binary/StringUtils.java
+++ b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/codec/binary/StringUtils.java
@@ -78,7 +78,10 @@ public class StringUtils {
         if (cs1 instanceof String && cs2 instanceof String) {
             return cs1.equals(cs2);
         }
-        return CharSequenceUtils.regionMatches(cs1, false, 0, cs2, 0, Math.max(cs1.length(), cs2.length()));
+        if (cs1.length() != cs2.length()) {
+            return false;
+        }
